Biodiversity data

As input, ecological models require georeferenced biodiversity occurrence data (e.g.Â species locations, whih is the response or dependent variable). Such information are widely available in digital format (e.g., online repositories provide data on species distributions like GBIF).

# always set a working directory

Download data with R

GBIF and OBIS contain worldwide occurrence records from observations as well as museum records.

recordsGBIF <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")

Merging different sources of biodiversity data

Binding different data sources to obtain a unique dataset.

# download GBIF records for a species (genus species)
recordsGBIF <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## 1298 records found
## 0-300-600-900-1200-1298 records downloaded
colnames(recordsGBIF)
## [1] "Name"      "Locality"  "Lon"       "Lat"       "Depth"     "dateYear" 
## [7] "dateMonth" "dateDay"
recordsOBIS <- getOccurrencesObis("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## Retrieved 242 records of approximately 242 (100%)
colnames(recordsGBIF)
## [1] "Name"      "Locality"  "Lon"       "Lat"       "Depth"     "dateYear" 
## [7] "dateMonth" "dateDay"
recordsInaturalist <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/inaturalist.csv",sep=",")
colnames(recordsInaturalist)
##  [1] "id"                               "observed_on_string"              
##  [3] "observed_on"                      "time_observed_at"                
##  [5] "time_zone"                        "out_of_range"                    
##  [7] "user_id"                          "user_login"                      
##  [9] "created_at"                       "updated_at"                      
## [11] "quality_grade"                    "license"                         
## [13] "url"                              "image_url"                       
## [15] "sound_url"                        "tag_list"                        
## [17] "description"                      "id_please"                       
## [19] "num_identification_agreements"    "num_identification_disagreements"
## [21] "captive_cultivated"               "oauth_application_id"            
## [23] "place_guess"                      "latitude"                        
## [25] "longitude"                        "positional_accuracy"             
## [27] "geoprivacy"                       "taxon_geoprivacy"                
## [29] "coordinates_obscured"             "positioning_method"              
## [31] "positioning_device"               "species_guess"                   
## [33] "scientific_name"                  "common_name"                     
## [35] "iconic_taxon_name"                "taxon_id"
# Subset occurrences to get only coordinates
recordsGBIF <- recordsGBIF[,c("Lon","Lat")]
recordsOBIS <- recordsOBIS[,c("Lon","Lat")]
recordsInaturalist <- recordsInaturalist[,c("longitude","latitude")]
colnames(recordsInaturalist) <- c("Lon","Lat")

records <- rbind(recordsGBIF,recordsOBIS,recordsInaturalist)
nrow(records)
## [1] 1550
plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Combined distribution records" , ylab="latitude", xlab="longitude")
points(records, pch=20, col="Black")

Georeferencing in R

Georeferencing is the process of assigning real-world coordinates to a locality (point in space, pixel in raster, etc.)

# get coordinates based on locality name
getCoordinates("Lisboa")
##         Lon      Lat
## 1 -9.138006 38.71306
# download the records for a species
records <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## 1298 records found

Data cleaning in R

Data âcleaningâ is particularly important for data sourced from data warehouses such as GBIF.

# remove NA coordinates
sum( is.na(records$Lon) )
## [1] 0
records <- records[which( ! is.na(records$Lon) ), ]

# remove duplicate coordinates
records <- records[ which( ! duplicated( records[,c("Lon","Lat")] ) ), ]

plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Clean distribution records" , ylab="latitude", xlab="longitude")
points(records[,3:4], pch=20, col="Black")

# remove records outside known distributions
# the species only occur from Morocco (NE Atlantic) to Ireland (NW Atlantic) and in the Azores 
# defineRegion(records)
# records <- selectRecords(records)

# remove records outside known vertical distribution
# the species only occur down to 80m depths
bathymetry <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/BathymetryDepthMean.tif")
depthUse <- extract(bathymetry,records[,c("Lon","Lat")])
head(depthUse)
## [1]  0  0 -3 -5  0 -3
hist(depthUse,breaks=50)

records <- records[ which(depthUse > -80) ,]

# identify and remove records on land
overLand <- whichOverLand(records)
length(overLand)
## [1] 140
records <- records[-overLand,]

plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Clean distribution records" , ylab="latitude", xlab="longitude")
points(records[,3:4], pch=20, col="Black")

nrow(records)
## [1] 360
Challenge 5.2

The main objetive of this challenge is to collect biodiversity data from GBIF and OBIS in R, clean records, produce a plot and save records for latter use.

# packages, data and functions needed to accomplish the challenge

# Species: Laminaria ochroleuca
# Information: The species only occur from morocco to Brittany (NE Atlantic), in the Azores and the Western Mediterranean Sea at maximum depths of 80m

# Use Recipe #1 
# 1. get records with getOccurrencesGBIF() and getOccurrencesObis()
# 2. populate NA coordinates 
# 3. remove NA coordinates 
# 4. remove duplicate coordinates with duplicated()
# 5. identify  records outside the know distibution (also depth)
# 6. remove records on land 
# 8. plot records with plot() and ggplot()
# 9. Save records with write.table()
